or\n* [[Emraan Hashmi]], Bollywood Actor; at Nibhana\n* [[Asha Sachdev]] at Sunset Heights\n* [[A.M. Naik]], CEO, Executive Chairman and Managing Director of [[Larsen & Toubro]] Limited\n* Playback Singer [[Kunal Ganjawalla]], his wife, singer [[Gayatri Ganjawala]], at Girnar Apartments\n* Vinod Mehra (Actor)\n* Sunil Agnihotri ( television series Chandrakanta director )\n* Bharat Bhushan ( veteran actor )\n* Meena Kumari ( veteran actress )\n* Manhar Bhagat ( Nirlon Owner )\n* Dj Aqeel\n* The famous Rembrandt Apartment.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* Bhatkal, Satyajit (editor: Lancy Fernandes). ''The Spirit of Lagaan: The extraordinary story of the creators of a classic''. [[Popular Prakashan]], 1 March 2002. {{ISBN|8179910032}}, 9788179910030. In Google Books under the title \"Eka svapn\u0101c\u0101 prav\u0101sa lag\u0101na\"\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://wikimapia.org/413815/Pali-Hill-Bandra Pali Hill, Bandra] at [[Wikimapia]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071116125838/http://www.naachgaana.com/2007/11/15/ek-bungalow-bane-nyaara/ Article about celebrity residents of Bandra/Pali Hill]\n* [http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-08-29/india/28298551_1_bungalows-stately-homes-madhu-poplai Apts replace stately bungalows at Pali Hill] [[Times of India]]\n\n[[Category:Hills of Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Neighbourhoods in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Bandra]]\n", "name_user": "Gdrged", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLandmarks:capitalization \"shinde\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pali_Hill"}
{"title_page": "Fire-breasted flowerpecker", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| image = Fire-breasted Flowerpecker Khangchendzonga National Park West Sikkim Sikkim India 29.10.2015.jpg\n| image_caption = Male of nominate subspecies from [[Khangchendzonga National Park]]\n| image2 = Dicaeum_ignipectus_female_(cropped).jpg\n| image2_caption = Female\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22717569/0 |title=''Dicaeum ignipectus'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Dicaeum\n| species = ignipectus\n| authority = ([[Edward Blyth|Blyth]], 1843)\n| synonyms = ''Myzanthe ignipectus''<br />''Micrura ignipectus''\n}}\n\nThe '''fire-breasted flowerpecker''' (''Dicaeum ignipectus'') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Dicaeidae]] found in the [[Indian Subcontinent]] and [[Southeast Asia]]. Like other flowerpeckers, this tiny bird feeds on fruits and plays an important role in the dispersal of fruiting plants.<ref name=ingle/><ref>{{cite journal|author=Corlett, Richard T|year=1998|title=Frugivory and seed dispersal by birds in Hong Kong shrubland.|journal=Forktail|volume=13|pages=23\u201327|url=http://orientalbirdclub.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Corlett-Frugivory.pdf}}</ref> Unlike many other species in the genus, this species has marked [[sexual dimorphism]] with the male having contrasting upper and lower parts with a distinctive bright orange breast patch. The female is dull coloured.\n\n== Description ==\nThe fire-breasted flowerpecker is a small flowerpecker with a small and dark bill. The male has glossy blue-black upperparts. The underside is buffy but a bright red breast patch. Starting below it and along the middle is a short black stripe going down till the belly. The female is dark olive above and buff below. The sides are olive and the bill has a pale base.<ref name=pcr>{{cite book|author=Rasmussen PC|author2=JC Anderton|last-author-amp=yes |year=2005 |title= Birds of South Asia: The Ripley Guide.|publisher= Smithsonian Institution & Lynx Edicions. |volume= 2 |pages=545\u2013546}}</ref>\n[[File:DicaeumIgnipectusGould.jpg|thumb|left|Lithograph by [[John Gould]] in the Birds of Asia (1850\u201383), volume 6, plate 14. [[T. C. Jerdon]] noted that he had in his ''Birds of India'', ''\"... omitted to mention the black streak extending along the middle of the abdomen from the termination of the scarlet breast-spot....\"''<ref>{{cite journal|author=Jerdon, TC |year=1872 |title=Supplementary notes to the \"Birds of India\" |journal=Ibis|volume=2 Third series |pages=1\u201321|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1872.tb05855.x|url=https://archive.org/stream/ibis23brit#page/19/mode/1up/}}</ref>]]\n\n[[File:Dicaeum ignipectus Nepal by Krishna (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Male of nominate race, [[Nepal]].]]\n\nWeighing just {{convert|7|-|9|g|oz|abbr=on}} and measuring under {{convert|7|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, it is one of the smallest flowerpeckers.<ref name=ingle>{{cite journal|journal=Oecologia|year=2003|volume=134|pages=251\u2013261|doi=10.1007/s00442-002-1081-7|author=Ingle, Nina R|title=Seed dispersal by wind, birds, and bats between Philippine montane rainforest and successional vegetation|jstor=4223499|pmid=12647166|issue=2|bibcode=2003Oecol.134..251I}}</ref> They are usually found at the tops of the trees especially on mistletoes. They have a shrill call given regularly and has been likened to snipping scissors and a staccato ''tsit''.<ref name=pcr/>\n\nThe species was first described by [[Edward Blyth]] in 1843 based on a specimen obtained from Nepal by [[Brian Houghton Hodgson|B H Hodgson]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=Blyth, E |year=1843|title=Mr. Blyth's monthly Report for December Meeting, 1842, with addenda subsequently appended.|journal=Journ. As. Soc. Bengal|volume=12 part 2 no 143|pages=983|url=https://archive.org/stream/journalasiatics31benggoog#page/n494/mode/1up }}</ref> The name was based on Hodgson's manuscripts but was published by Blyth.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Rothschild, Lord |year=1921 |title= On a collection of birds from West-Central and North-Western Yunnan. |journal=[[Novitates Zoologicae]] |volume=28|pages=14\u201367 [57] |url=https://archive.org/details/novitateszoologi28lond |doi=10.5962/bhl.part.26912 }}</ref> The type specimen claimed to have been deposited at the British Museum is said to be lost, but may exist in the collection of the Asiatic Society museum in Calcutta.<ref>{{cite book|author=Rachel L. M. Warren|author2=C.J.O. Harrison|last-author-amp=yes|publisher=Trustees of the British Museum (Natural History)|year=1971|title=Type specimens of Birds in The Natural History Museum| volume=2|url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/jdsml/research-curation/research/projects/birdtype/}}</ref>\n\nIt has been said to be \"the smallest bird of India\" or \"perhaps the smallest\":<ref>{{cite book|author=Dewar, Douglas |year=1915 |title= Birds of the Indian hills. |publisher=John Lane, London|url=https://archive.org/details/birdsofindianhil00dewa |page=[https://archive.org/details/birdsofindianhil00dewa/page/76 76]}} ''\"The fire-breasted flower-pecker (Dicaeum ignipectus) is perhaps the smallest bird in India.\"'' p. 76</ref>\n{{quote|... the Fire-breasted Myzanthe (''Myzanthe ignipectus''), a bird which is remarkable as being the smallest bird of India. So very small is this beautiful little bird, that an adult specimen is hardly two and a half inches in total length, and weighs only three and a half drachms. In its habits it is very like the Dicaeum, frequenting the tops of trees, and keeping itself well out of sight...|John George Wood, 1862<ref>{{cite book|author=Wood, John George |year=1862|title=The illustrated Natural History.|volume= 3 |page=[https://archive.org/details/illustratednatur00wooduoft/page/210 210]|url=https://archive.org/details/illustratednatur00wooduoft}}</ref>}}\n\n== Distribution ==\nIt is found widely distributed along the sub-Himalayan region in [[India]], [[Nepal]], [[Bhutan]], [[Bangladesh]]<ref>{{cite journal |author=Khan, MMH |year=2004 |title=Fire-breasted Flowerpecker ''Dicaeum ignipectus'': the first record for Bangladesh. |journal=Forktail |volume=20 |page=120 |url=http://www.orientalbirdclub.org/publications/forktail/20pdfs/Khan-Flowerpecker.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080704121629/http://www.orientalbirdclub.org/publications/forktail/20pdfs/Khan-Flowerpecker.pdf |archivedate=2008-07-04 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.hbw.com/species/fire-breasted-flowerpecker-dicaeum-ignipectus | title=Fire-breasted Flowerpecker (Dicaeum ignipectus)}}</ref> and extends into Southeast Asia into Indonesia, Laos, Thailand, Vietnam, Taiwan, Malaysia and the Philippines. Its natural [[habitat]]s are [[temperate forest]], [[subtropical or tropical moist lowland forest]], and subtropical or tropical moist [[montane forest]].\n[[File:DicaeumFormosumGronvold.jpg|thumb|''D. i. formosum'']]\nSeveral populations have been named as subspecies. The nominate ''ignipectus'' found along the Himalayas into Southeast Asia on the mainland. The remaining are insular populations and include ''formosum'' of Taiwan, ''luzoniense'' of Luzon, ''bonga'' of Samar and ''apo'' of the Negros and Mindanao. The species itself forms a superspecies complex with ''[[Dicaeum monticolum]]'', ''[[Dicaeum celebicum|D. celebicum]]'', ''[[Dicaeum sanguinolentum|D. sanguinolentum]]'' and ''[[Dicaeum hirundinaceum|D. hirundinaceum]]'' which are sometimes all treated as one species. Hybridization with ''[[Dicaeum cruentatum]]'' has been suggested.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Baker, EC Stuart |year=1898|title= Probably hybrid between the scarlet-backed flower-pecker (''Dicaeum cruentatum'') and the Fire-breasted Flowerpecker (''D. ignipectus'').|journal= J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=11|page=467|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/30157220}}</ref><ref name=finn/> Many island forms show patterns of very restricted ranges or micro-endemism and it has been suggested that these be treated with care for conservation planning.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Peterson, A T|year=2006|title=Taxonomy is important in conservation: a preliminary reassessment of Philippine species-level bird taxonomy|journal=Bird Conservation International|volume=16|pages=155\u2013173|doi=10.1017/S0959270906000256|url=http://specify5.specifysoftware.org/Informatics/bios/biostownpeterson/P_BCI_2006.pdf|issue=2|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728044134/http://specify5.specifysoftware.org/Informatics/bios/biostownpeterson/P_BCI_2006.pdf|archivedate=2011-07-28}}</ref>\n\nThe populations found in the Philippines have males with the underparts similar to ''D. monticolum'' while the females have a steel-green gloss on the upperparts unlike the dull green of more northern forms. The Sumatran population ''beccarii'' is the most distinct form and differs also from ''D. sanguinolentum''. The males have a steel-green gloss on the upper parts and lack the throat patch while the females have greenish upperparts and lack the red rump.<ref name=finn>{{cite journal|author=Salomonsen, Finn|year=1961|title=Notes on flowerpeckers (Aves, Dicaeidae). 4, Dicaeum igniferum and its derivatives. American Museum novitates ; no. 2057|hdl=2246/3436|journal=American Museum Novitates|volume=2057}}</ref>\n\nThroughout its range, the species is found in high mountains above 1000 metres but in China, they may be found during winter at lower altitudes.<ref name=finn/>\n\n== Behaviour and ecology ==\nLike many other flowerpeckers, they disperse the seeds of mistletoes. In the Nepal Himalayas, they have been found to be important dispersers of ''[[Scurrula]]'' species.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Devkota, M P|year=2005 |title= Mistletoes of the Annapurna Conservation Area, Central Nepal Himalayas |journal=Journal of Japanese Botany |volume=80|issue=1|pages=27\u201336}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Nainital]] they are said to breed in June and July. The nest is pendant and purse like, opening on the side towards the top. The nest is thin and felt-like, made up of the hairy coverings of stems from mistletoes. The nest is lined with moss and soft grass. Two or three eggs are laid and both sexes incubate and take care of the young.<ref>{{cite book|author=Hume, AO|year=1890 |title= The nest and eggs of Indian Birds. |publisher=R. H. Porter, London. |volume=2|page=[https://archive.org/details/nestseggsofindia02hume/page/272 272]|url=https://archive.org/details/nestseggsofindia02hume}}</ref><ref name=hbk>{{cite book|author=Ali S|author2=S D Ripley|last-author-amp=yes|year=1999|title=Handbook of the birds of India and Pakistan|edition=2nd|volume=10|publisher=Oxford University Press|pages=18\u201319}}</ref>\n\nIn Hong Kong, their population is believed to have increased with maturation of restored forest. They were first recorded in 1954 but have starter breed regularly since 1975.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Leven, MR|author2=RT Corlett|last-author-amp=yes |year=2004 |title= Invasive birds in Hong Kong, China |journal=Ornithological Science|volume= 3|issue=1|pages=43\u201355 |doi=10.2326/osj.3.43|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==References==<!-- Forktail16:147. -->\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== Other sources ==\n* Lin, Chen-Wei (2006). Studying breeding bird densities in Meifeng Area by Territory mapping. M Sc. Thesis. National Taiwan University. [http://homepage.ntu.edu.tw/~ding/advising/2006%20Lin.pdf PDF]\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://ibc.lynxeds.com/species/fire-breasted-flowerpecker-dicaeum-ignipectus The Internet Bird Collection]\n* [http://www.xeno-canto.org/asia/species.php?query=Dicaeum+ignipectus Call recordings on Xeno-Canto]\n\n{{Dicaeidae}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1441623}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:flowerpicker, fire-breasted}}\n[[Category:Dicaeum|fire-breasted flowerpecker]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Himalayas]]\n[[Category:Birds of Northeast India]]\n[[Category:Birds of Hainan]]\n[[Category:Birds of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Birds of Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Birds of Southeast Asia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1843|fire-breasted flowerpecker]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| image = Fire-breasted Flowerpecker Khangchendzonga National Park West Sikkim Sikkim India 29.10.2015.jpg\n| image_caption = Male of nominate subspecies from [[Khangchendzonga National Park]]\n| image2 = Dicaeum_ignipectus_female_(cropped).jpg\n| image2_caption = Female\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22717569/0 |title=''Dicaeum ignipectus'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Dicaeum\n| species = ignipectus\n| authority = ([[Edward Blyth|Blyth]], 1843)\n| synonyms = ''Myzanthe ignipectus''<br />''Micrura ignipectus''\n}}\n\nThe '''fire-breasted flowerpecker''' (''Dicaeum ignipectus'') is a species of [[bird]] in the [[Dicaeidae]] family found in the [[Indian Subcontinent]] and [[Southeast Asia]]. Like other flowerpeckers, this tiny bird feeds on fruits and plays an important role in the dispersal of fruiting plants.<ref name=ingle/><ref>{{cite journal|author=Corlett, Richard T|year=1998|title=Frugivory and seed dispersal by birds in Hong Kong shrubland.|journal=Forktail|volume=13|pages=23\u201327|url=http://orientalbirdclub.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Corlett-Frugivory.pdf}}</ref> Unlike many other species in the genus, this species has marked [[sexual dimorphism]] with the male having contrasting upper and lower parts with a distinctive bright orange breast patch. The female is dull coloured.\n\n== Description ==\nThe fire-breasted flowerpecker is a small flowerpecker with a small and dark bill. The male has glossy blue-black upperparts. The underside is buffy but a bright red breast patch. Starting below it and along the middle is a short black stripe going down till the belly. The female is dark olive above and buff below. The sides are olive and the bill has a pale base.<ref name=pcr>{{cite book|author=Rasmussen PC|author2=JC Anderton|last-author-amp=yes |year=2005 |title= Birds of South Asia: The Ripley Guide.|publisher= Smithsonian Institution & Lynx Edicions. |volume= 2 |pages=545\u2013546}}</ref>\n[[File:DicaeumIgnipectusGould.jpg|thumb|left|Lithograph by [[John Gould]] in the Birds of Asia (1850\u201383), volume 6, plate 14. [[T. C. Jerdon]] noted that he had in his ''Birds of India'', ''\"... omitted to mention the black streak extending along the middle of the abdomen from the termination of the scarlet breast-spot....\"''<ref>{{cite journal|author=Jerdon, TC |year=1872 |title=Supplementary notes to the \"Birds of India\" |journal=Ibis|volume=2 Third series |pages=1\u201321|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1872.tb05855.x|url=https://archive.org/stream/ibis23brit#page/19/mode/1up/}}</ref>]]\n\n[[File:Dicaeum ignipectus Nepal by Krishna (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Male of nominate race, [[Nepal]].]]\n\nWeighing just {{convert|7|-|9|g|oz|abbr=on}} and measuring under {{convert|7|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, it is one of the smallest flowerpeckers.<ref name=ingle>{{cite journal|journal=Oecologia|year=2003|volume=134|pages=251\u2013261|doi=10.1007/s00442-002-1081-7|author=Ingle, Nina R|title=Seed dispersal by wind, birds, and bats between Philippine montane rainforest and successional vegetation|jstor=4223499|pmid=12647166|issue=2|bibcode=2003Oecol.134..251I}}</ref> They are usually found at the tops of the trees especially on mistletoes. They have a shrill call given regularly and has been likened to snipping scissors and a staccato ''tsit''.<ref name=pcr/>\n\nThe species was first described by [[Edward Blyth]] in 1843 based on a specimen obtained from Nepal by [[Brian Houghton Hodgson|B H Hodgson]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=Blyth, E |year=1843|title=Mr. Blyth's monthly Report for December Meeting, 1842, with addenda subsequently appended.|journal=Journ. As. Soc. Bengal|volume=12 part 2 no 143|pages=983|url=https://archive.org/stream/journalasiatics31benggoog#page/n494/mode/1up }}</ref> The name was based on Hodgson's manuscripts but was published by Blyth.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Rothschild, Lord |year=1921 |title= On a collection of birds from West-Central and North-Western Yunnan. |journal=[[Novitates Zoologicae]] |volume=28|pages=14\u201367 [57] |url=https://archive.org/details/novitateszoologi28lond |doi=10.5962/bhl.part.26912 }}</ref> The type specimen claimed to have been deposited at the British Museum is said to be lost, but may exist in the collection of the Asiatic Society museum in Calcutta.<ref>{{cite book|author=Rachel L. M. Warren|author2=C.J.O. Harrison|last-author-amp=yes|publisher=Trustees of the British Museum (Natural History)|year=1971|title=Type specimens of Birds in The Natural History Museum| volume=2|url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/jdsml/research-curation/research/projects/birdtype/}}</ref>\n\nIt has been said to be \"the smallest bird of India\" or \"perhaps the smallest\":<ref>{{cite book|author=Dewar, Douglas |year=1915 |title= Birds of the Indian hills. |publisher=John Lane, London|url=https://archive.org/details/birdsofindianhil00dewa |page=[https://archive.org/details/birdsofindianhil00dewa/page/76 76]}} ''\"The fire-breasted flower-pecker (Dicaeum ignipectus) is perhaps the smallest bird in India.\"'' p. 76</ref>\n{{quote|... the Fire-breasted Myzanthe (''Myzanthe ignipectus''), a bird which is remarkable as being the smallest bird of India. So very small is this beautiful little bird, that an adult specimen is hardly two and a half inches in total length, and weighs only three and a half drachms. In its habits it is very like the Dicaeum, frequenting the tops of trees, and keeping itself well out of sight...|John George Wood, 1862<ref>{{cite book|author=Wood, John George |year=1862|title=The illustrated Natural History.|volume= 3 |page=[https://archive.org/details/illustratednatur00wooduoft/page/210 210]|url=https://archive.org/details/illustratednatur00wooduoft}}</ref>}}\n\n== Distribution ==\nIt is found widely distributed along the sub-Himalayan region in [[India]], [[Nepal]], [[Bhutan]], [[Bangladesh]]<ref>{{cite journal |author=Khan, MMH |year=2004 |title=Fire-breasted Flowerpecker ''Dicaeum ignipectus'': the first record for Bangladesh. |journal=Forktail |volume=20 |page=120 |url=http://www.orientalbirdclub.org/publications/forktail/20pdfs/Khan-Flowerpecker.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080704121629/http://www.orientalbirdclub.org/publications/forktail/20pdfs/Khan-Flowerpecker.pdf |archivedate=2008-07-04 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.hbw.com/species/fire-breasted-flowerpecker-dicaeum-ignipectus | title=Fire-breasted Flowerpecker (Dicaeum ignipectus)}}</ref> and extends into Southeast Asia into Indonesia, Laos, Thailand, Vietnam, Taiwan, Malaysia and the Philippines. Its natural [[habitat]]s are temperate [[forest]]s, subtropical or tropical moist lowland forests, and subtropical or tropical moist [[montane forest]]s.\n[[File:DicaeumFormosumGronvold.jpg|thumb|''D. i. formosum'']]\nSeveral populations have been named as subspecies. The nominate ''ignipectus'' found along the Himalayas into Southeast Asia on the mainland. The remaining are insular populations and include ''formosum'' of Taiwan, ''luzoniense'' of Luzon, ''bonga'' of Samar and ''apo'' of the Negros and Mindanao. The species itself forms a superspecies complex with ''[[Dicaeum monticolum]]'', ''[[Dicaeum celebicum|D. celebicum]]'', ''[[Dicaeum sanguinolentum|D. sanguinolentum]]'' and ''[[Dicaeum hirundinaceum|D. hirundinaceum]]'' which are sometimes all treated as one species. Hybridization with ''[[Dicaeum cruentatum]]'' has been suggested.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Baker, EC Stuart |year=1898|title= Probably hybrid between the scarlet-backed flower-pecker (''Dicaeum cruentatum'') and the Fire-breasted Flowerpecker (''D. ignipectus'').|journal= J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=11|page=467|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/30157220}}</ref><ref name=finn/> Many island forms show patterns of very restricted ranges or micro-endemism and it has been suggested that these be treated with care for conservation planning.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Peterson, A T|year=2006|title=Taxonomy is important in conservation: a preliminary reassessment of Philippine species-level bird taxonomy|journal=Bird Conservation International|volume=16|pages=155\u2013173|doi=10.1017/S0959270906000256|url=http://specify5.specifysoftware.org/Informatics/bios/biostownpeterson/P_BCI_2006.pdf|issue=2|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728044134/http://specify5.specifysoftware.org/Informatics/bios/biostownpeterson/P_BCI_2006.pdf|archivedate=2011-07-28}}</ref>\n\nThe populations found in the Philippines have males with the underparts similar to ''D. monticolum'' while the females have a steel-green gloss on the upperparts unlike the dull green of more northern forms. The Sumatran population ''beccarii'' is the most distinct form and differs also from ''D. sanguinolentum''. The males have a steel-green gloss on the upper parts and lack the throat patch while the females have greenish upperparts and lack the red rump.<ref name=finn>{{cite journal|author=Salomonsen, Finn|year=1961|title=Notes on flowerpeckers (Aves, Dicaeidae). 4, Dicaeum igniferum and its derivatives. American Museum novitates ; no. 2057|hdl=2246/3436|journal=American Museum Novitates|volume=2057}}</ref>\n\nThroughout its range, the species is found in high mountains above 1000 metres but in China, they may be found during winter at lower altitudes.<ref name=finn/>\n\n== Behaviour and ecology ==\nLike many other flowerpeckers, they disperse the seeds of mistletoes. In the Nepal Himalayas, they have been found to be important dispersers of ''[[Scurrula]]'' species.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Devkota, M P|year=2005 |title= Mistletoes of the Annapurna Conservation Area, Central Nepal Himalayas |journal=Journal of Japanese Botany |volume=80|issue=1|pages=27\u201336}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Nainital]] they are said to breed in June and July. The nest is pendant and purse like, opening on the side towards the top. The nest is thin and felt-like, made up of the hairy coverings of stems from mistletoes. The nest is lined with moss and soft grass. Two or three eggs are laid and both sexes incubate and take care of the young.<ref>{{cite book|author=Hume, AO|year=1890 |title= The nest and eggs of Indian Birds. |publisher=R. H. Porter, London. |volume=2|page=[https://archive.org/details/nestseggsofindia02hume/page/272 272]|url=https://archive.org/details/nestseggsofindia02hume}}</ref><ref name=hbk>{{cite book|author=Ali S|author2=S D Ripley|last-author-amp=yes|year=1999|title=Handbook of the birds of India and Pakistan|edition=2nd|volume=10|publisher=Oxford University Press|pages=18\u201319}}</ref>\n\nIn Hong Kong, their population is believed to have increased with maturation of restored forests. They were first recorded in 1954 but have starter breed regularly since 1975.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Leven, MR|author2=RT Corlett|last-author-amp=yes |year=2004 |title= Invasive birds in Hong Kong, China |journal=Ornithological Science|volume= 3|issue=1|pages=43\u201355 |doi=10.2326/osj.3.43|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==References==<!-- Forktail16:147. -->\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== Other sources ==\n* Lin, Chen-Wei (2006). Studying breeding bird densities in Meifeng Area by Territory mapping. M Sc. Thesis. National Taiwan University. [http://homepage.ntu.edu.tw/~ding/advising/2006%20Lin.pdf PDF]\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://ibc.lynxeds.com/species/fire-breasted-flowerpecker-dicaeum-ignipectus The Internet Bird Collection]\n* [http://www.xeno-canto.org/asia/species.php?query=Dicaeum+ignipectus Call recordings on Xeno-Canto]\n\n{{Dicaeidae}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1441623}}\n\n